  "text": "RAMMING AND APPENZELLER-HERZOG potential support of this, antioxidant treatment mimicked the inhibitory effect of Ero1a knockdown on ER calcium release [CITATION_1] . However, as the CHOP-Ero1a-IP 3 R1 signaling pathway induces NADPH oxidase 2-derived reactive oxygen species (ROS), which in turn further amplify CHOP (33), the application of antioxidants did not necessarily exert its effect by counteracting Ero1a activity. Moreover, given the tight regulatory mechanisms that prevent excessive disulfide and H 2 O 2 synthesis by Ero1a (see above), its increased expression does not per se hyperoxidize the ER (6, 7). The probably minor contribution of Ero1-derived ROS to ER-stressinduced cell death has recently been evaluated in detail elsewhere (4) .",
